    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "e116f01f38d7e9c39c5f158c488d4c9b3b4c4b238257612adaa0c8725b7c06df",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "For example,\\[\\frac{1}{3}+\\frac{1}{4}+\\frac{1}{5}+\\frac{1}{6}+\\frac{1}{20}=1.\\]This is still open even if $\\lvert I_2\\rvert=1$. It is perhaps true with two intervals replaced by any $k$ intervals."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "5d534a6d867e81945af1c14f91d10a069e0d178cea51b411a21fa15b03e63d09",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Is it true that there are only finitely many pairs of intervals $I_1,I_2$ such that\\[\\sum_{n_1\\in I_1}\\frac{1}{n_1}+\\sum_{n_2\\in I_2}\\frac{1}{n_2}\\in \\mathbb{N}?\\]"
    }
  },
